Yes, **that makes perfect sense!** Let me map this out:

## Proposed Architecture

### 1. **`LLMService`** (SciJava Service - Singleton, Stateless)

**Responsibilities:**
- Discover available LLM provider plugins
- Create/manage LLM instances (chat models)
- Handle API key retrieval (delegates to `APIKeyService`)
- Factory methods for creating assistants
- **Does NOT** hold conversation state

```java
@Service
public class LLMService extends AbstractService {

    @Parameter
    private PluginService pluginService;

    @Parameter
    private APIKeyService apiKeyService;

    // Discover available providers
    public List<LLMProviderPlugin> getAvailableProviders() {
        return pluginService.createInstancesOfType(LLMProviderPlugin.class);
    }

    // Factory: Create a chat model for a provider
    public ChatLanguageModel createChatModel(String providerName, String modelName) {
        LLMProviderPlugin provider = findProvider(providerName);
        String apiKey = apiKeyService.getApiKey(providerName);
        return provider.createChatModel(apiKey, modelName);
    }

    // Factory: Create an AI service instance
    public <T> T createAssistant(Class<T> assistantInterface, 
                                  ChatLanguageModel model,
                                  ChatMemory memory) {
        return AiServices.builder(assistantInterface)
            .chatLanguageModel(model)
            .chatMemory(memory)
            .build();
    }
}
```

### 2. **`LLMProviderPlugin`** (SciJava Plugin - Multiple Instances)

**One plugin per provider** (OpenAI, Anthropic, Gemini):

```java
@Plugin(type = LLMProviderPlugin.class, name = "OpenAI")
public class OpenAIProviderPlugin implements LLMProviderPlugin {

    @Override
    public String getName() { return "OpenAI"; }

    @Override
    public List<String> getAvailableModels() {
        return Arrays.asList("gpt-4o", "gpt-4-turbo", "gpt-3.5-turbo");
    }

    @Override
    public ChatLanguageModel createChatModel(String apiKey, String modelName) {
        return OpenAiChatModel.builder()
            .apiKey(apiKey)
            .modelName(modelName)
            .build();
    }

    @Override
    public StreamingChatLanguageModel createStreamingChatModel(String apiKey, String modelName) {
        return OpenAiStreamingChatModel.builder()
            .apiKey(apiKey)
            .modelName(modelName)
            .build();
    }
}
```

### 3. **`ConversationManager`** (Stateful - User Creates Instances)

**NOT a service** - users create instances for each conversation:

```java
public class ConversationManager {
    private final ChatLanguageModel model;
    private final ChatMemory memory;
    private final FijiAssistant assistant;

    public ConversationManager(LLMService llmService, 
                              String providerName, 
                              String modelName) {
        this.model = llmService.createChatModel(providerName, modelName);
        this.memory = MessageWindowChatMemory.withMaxMessages(20);
        this.assistant = llmService.createAssistant(
            FijiAssistant.class, 
            model, 
            memory
        );
    }

    public String chat(String message, String context) {
        return assistant.chat(context, message);
    }

    public void clearHistory() {
        memory.clear();
    }

    public List<ChatMessage> getHistory() {
        return memory.messages();
    }
}
```

### 4. **Usage Pattern**

```java
// In your UI code
@Parameter
private LLMService llmService;

// User selects provider and model
ConversationManager conversation = new ConversationManager(
    llmService,
    "OpenAI",
    "gpt-4o"
);

// Chat
String response = conversation.chat("How do I segment cells?", buildContext());

// Later, create a new conversation
ConversationManager newConvo = new ConversationManager(...);
```

## Why This Structure Works

âœ… **`LLMService` is stateless** - just factories and plugin management  
âœ… **Provider plugins** - Easy to add new LLM providers  
âœ… **`ConversationManager` holds state** - One per chat window  
âœ… **Follows SciJava patterns** - Services manage plugins, instances hold state  
âœ… **Clean separation** - UI creates ConversationManagers, doesn't talk to LangChain4j directly

## Package Structure

```
sc.fiji.llm.service/
  â”œâ”€â”€ LLMService.java              (SciJava Service)
  â””â”€â”€ APIKeyService.java           (SciJava Service)

sc.fiji.llm.provider/
  â”œâ”€â”€ LLMProviderPlugin.java       (Plugin interface)
  â”œâ”€â”€ OpenAIProviderPlugin.java
  â”œâ”€â”€ AnthropicProviderPlugin.java
  â””â”€â”€ GeminiProviderPlugin.java

sc.fiji.llm.conversation/
  â”œâ”€â”€ ConversationManager.java     (Stateful, user-created)
  â”œâ”€â”€ FijiAssistant.java          (LangChain4j AI Service interface)
  â””â”€â”€ ChatMemory utilities

sc.fiji.llm.context/
  â””â”€â”€ Context building stuff
```

Does this structure align with your thinking? Want me to draft the actual code for `LLMService` and `LLMProviderPlugin`?

